{{for|the Nobel laureate|Daniel Nathans}} {{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st century Philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Daniel O. Nathan''' |birth_date = |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = | institutions = [[Texas Tech University]] |main_interests = [[aesthetics]], [[ethical theory]], [[philosophy of law]] |notable_ideas = Paradox of Intentionalism | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Illinois at Chicago]] (M.A. and Ph.D.), [[University of Michigan]] (A.B.) |influences = |influenced = |awards = }}
'''Daniel O. Nathan''' is an American philosopher and Professor of [[Philosophy]] at [[Texas Tech University]]. He is known for his expertise on [[aesthetics]], [[ethical theory]], and [[philosophy of law]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=De Clercq|first1=Rafael|title=The aesthetic creation theory of art|journal=[[Sztuka i Filozofia]]|date=2009|volume=35|url=https://philarchive.org/archive/DECTAC-3}}</ref> Nathan defends an [[Authorial intent|anti-intentionalist position]] in [[aesthetic interpretation]] and believes that intentionalism stems from a faulty analogy between an artwork and an utterance for communication.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Robinson|first1=Jenefer|title=Review of Contemporary Debates in Aesthetics and the Philosophy of Art|journal=[[Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews]]|date=17 February 2007|url=http://ndpr.nd.edu/news/contemporary-debates-in-aesthetics-and-the-philosophy-of-art/|accessdate=27 December 2017|issn=1538-1617}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Eden|first1=Brad|title=Review of "Contemporary debates in aesthetics and the philosophy of art"|journal=[[Consciousness, Literature and the Arts]]|date=December 2005|volume=6|url=http://www.dmd27.org/kieran.html|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Carroll|first1=Noël|title=Beyond Aesthetics: Philosophical Essays|date=2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521786560|pages=417|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t4IHIuuxFHcC&pg=PA417&lpg=PA417&dq=Daniel+Nathan+aesthetics&source=bl&ots=seLJ4SHS0M&sig=R9ZgOcs1WH7LRzt4aqFvVyGuQ5Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF-ebfnqrYAhUNDuwKHfXCCfgQ6AEIUDAI#v=onepage&q=Daniel%20Nathan%20aesthetics&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nathan's Paradox of Intentionalism|url=http://jay-odenbaugh.squarespace.com/phil-203-philosophy-of-art-beauty/2014/4/16/nathans-paradox-of-intentionalism|website=Jay Odenbaugh|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Selleri|first1=Andrea|title=Oscar Wilde and Authorialism|url=http://www.authorship.ugent.be/article/view/1086/1103|website=Authorship|accessdate=27 December 2017|language=en|date=28 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aesthetic Anti-Intentionalism: Art Tells Its Own Story|url=https://rwadholm.wordpress.com/2013/09/26/aesthetic-anti-intentionalism-art-tells-its-own-story/|website=Bob's Noggin Blog|accessdate=27 December 2017|date=26 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Nathan on Intentions & Interpretation|url=http://web.mnstate.edu/gracyk/courses/web%20publishing/Daniel%20Nathan%20on%20intentions-LectureNotes.htm|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Braddock|first1=Matthew|title=Actual intentionalism, interpretation, and ethical criticism|journal=Postgraduate Journal of Aesthetics|date=August 2006|volume= 3|issue= 2|url=http://www.pjaesthetics.org/index.php/pjaesthetics/article/download/48/45|accessdate=28 December 2017}}</ref>
